{
  "text": "This may be true, but it also need not be the case. Cognitively elaborate computations, such as those ascribed to the mirror neuron system, could remain distributed and taken on by a set of interacting brain circuits and systems. For instance, the model of imitative control outlined in Figure 4 is always a product of representation and control, but the content and relative weights assigned to each component can vary. Of course, future research is required to test between these possibilities. More generally, emphasising the integration of information across distributed architectures [CITATION_1] , may have a positive impact on continuing debates regarding functional claims over segregated circuits, such as the mirror neuron system [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "205504722",
